  "text": "The alerting evaluation scheduler in Grafana implements a ticker-based system to periodically evaluate alert rules. The core flow is as follows:\n\n## Ticker Generation (pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/ticker/ticker.go)\nThe `T.run()` method (line 55) is the main ticker goroutine that generates ticks at regular intervals specified by `baseInterval`. It emits time.Time values to the channel C at predictable times. The ticker is designed to queue up ticks rather than drop them, allowing downstream components to detect when they're falling behind.\n\n## Scheduler Main Loop (pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/schedule.go)\nThe scheduler coordinates the evaluation flow:\n\n1. **schedule.Run()** (line 177): Initializes the ticker with the base interval and invokes schedulePeriodic().\n\n2. **schedule.schedulePeriodic()** (line 248): The main event loop that receives ticks from the ticker's C channel. For each tick received, it calls processTick() and measures the time taken via the \"schedule_periodic_duration_seconds\" metric.\n\n3. **schedule.processTick()** (line 278): For each scheduler tick, this method:\n   - Updates the registry of schedulable alert rules\n   - Identifies which rules are ready to run based on their evaluation intervals\n   - Schedules the evaluations by calling runJobFn() for each ready-to-run rule\n\n4. **schedule.runJobFn()** (line 430): This is the critical method that detects evaluation cycle overruns. It:\n   - Calls `next.ruleRoutine.Eval(&next.Evaluation)` which returns `(success, dropped)`\n   - When `dropped != nil`, it means a previous evaluation was not processed before the next tick arrived\n   - Logs the warning: \"Tick dropped because alert rule evaluation is too slow\" (line 442)\n   - Increments the Prometheus metric `grafana_alerting_schedule_rule_evaluations_missed_total` (line 444)\n\n## Evaluation Cycle Overrun Detection (pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/alert_rule.go)\nThe `alertRule.Eval()` method (line 206) implements the key detection logic:\n\n1. Performs a non-blocking read from `a.evalCh` (line 214): `select { case droppedMsg = <-a.evalCh: default: }`\n2. If there's already a message in the channel that wasn't processed, it captures it as `droppedMsg`\n3. Sends the new evaluation to the channel (line 219)\n4. Returns both `success` (true/false) and the `droppedMsg` (which could be nil or the unprocessed evaluation)\n\nWhen a dropped message is returned (not nil), it indicates that the alert rule's evaluation routine was still processing the previous evaluation when the next tick arrived. This is the evaluation cycle overrun condition.\n\n## Metrics (pkg/services/ngalert/metrics/scheduler.go)\nThe `Scheduler` struct maintains the `EvaluationMissed` metric (line 33), which is a CounterVec tracking missed evaluations per organization and rule title. The metric name is `grafana_alerting_schedule_rule_evaluations_missed_total` and its help text is \"The total number of rule evaluations missed due to a slow rule evaluation.\"\n\nIn summary: The scheduler ticks at baseInterval (default 10s), schedules rule evaluations, and detects overruns when an evaluation routine hasn't finished processing the previous evaluation before the next tick arrives. When overruns are detected, the scheduler logs a warning and increments the missed evaluations metric."
